answers.body_markdown:
There are a number of different things going on here.

The method returns a `Supplier&lt;Map&lt;...&gt;&gt;`. The lambda expression `() -&gt; new HashMap&lt;&gt;() ...` returns an instance of the interface `Supplier` which returns a `HashMap`.

Also, it doesn&#39;t return a plain `HashMap`; an anonymous subclass of `HashMap` is being created here because of the outer `{ ... }`.

The inner `{ ... }` is an [instance initializer block](https://dzone.com/articles/instance-initializers-java) which is used to put stuff in the `HashMap` (two entries with keys `true` and `false` and each an `ArrayList` as the value).

This is using the [double-brace initialization trick](https://www.jesperdj.com/2016/07/19/dont-use-the-double-brace-initialization-trick/). (That link points to a blogpost written by me that explains why I dislike that trick).

A better way to write this (if you&#39;re using Java 9 or newer) that doesn&#39;t use the double-brace initialization trick is like this:

    public Supplier&lt;Map&lt;Boolean, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;&gt; supplier() {
        return () -&gt; Map.of(
            false, new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(),
            true, new ArrayList&lt;&gt;());
    }

I don&#39;t know if you run this piece of code but I tried to run it and I have to add 

    return () -&gt; new HashMap&lt;Boolean, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;()
Otherwise, @Jesper already gave you a good answer. 
Below, it is a little explanation about lambda expressions.

    () -&gt; ... 
is a lambda expression with zero parameters. 
You can use a lambda expression as a parameter, but you need to have a `@FunctionalInterface`. 
You can look at `forEach` method from `Iterable` class from Java.

    default void forEach(Consumer&lt;? super T&gt; var1)

In this case the consumer is a `FunctionalInterface`:

    @FunctionalInterface
    public interface Consumer&lt;T&gt; 

Basically, with lambda, you can send the body of the method as parameter. If you have a list with Strings named `stringList`, you can pass as parameter for `forEach` a lambda expression in order to print all the elements:

    stringList.forEach(elem -&gt; {
                System.out.println(elem);
            });
This lambda expression has one parameter, `elem`. You can have zero, one, or many parameters in a lambda expression.

